  "report": {
    "sections": {
      "What we found": "The estimate that stands out most is the chance of a longer-than-usual hospital stay during this admission \u2014 the model puts this at about 32%, and while that model is considered reliable, its confidence here is on the lower side, so it's best read as a rough signal rather than a firm figure. A reliable model also estimates a higher-than-usual chance of not surviving the next 12 months, again with lower confidence. Alongside these, your recorded labs show a few values below the usual range: a low albumin (2.9), a low hemoglobin (8.5), and a low platelet count (95), with a mildly elevated glucose (152) and a somewhat low potassium (3.4). Your blood pressure and heart rate also swung quite widely at times. Please remember these are model estimates and snapshots, not confirmed diagnoses.",
      "What may be contributing": "The prolonged-stay estimate leans on your blood urea nitrogen, oxygen levels, and heart rate \u2014 and your records do show wide heart-rate swings (a maximum of 151 at one point) even though your oxygen readings stayed reassuringly high. The 12-month estimate is shaped largely by your age together with your albumin and platelet levels, and both of those are recorded on the low side. Low albumin, low hemoglobin, and low platelets tend to travel together as a general picture of nutritional and blood status, which may be why they surface across more than one estimate. These are associations the model has picked up, not proven causes.",
      "What this means": "Taken together, the picture is one that warrants attention but is far from settled. Even the highest forward estimate sits below one in three, meaning the more likely path is that these outcomes don't happen \u2014 and the lower confidence on these figures is a real reason to treat them cautiously. The model also suggests hypertension is fairly likely to be part of your health background, which fits with the higher blood pressure peaks in your record. A separate estimate about readmission comes from a model flagged as less reliable, so it carries little weight and shouldn't be a focus.",
      "What to do next": "It would be worth reviewing these results with your care team, especially the low albumin, hemoglobin, and platelet readings and the elevated glucose, so they can interpret them in the full context of your health. Asking what the blood pressure and heart rate variability might reflect, and whether any follow-up monitoring is useful, is a reasonable conversation to have. Bring this summary along as a starting point for questions rather than conclusions.",
      "When to seek care urgently": "Seek urgent care right away for chest pain or pressure, sudden trouble breathing, fainting or severe dizziness, unusual or heavy bleeding or bruising, confusion, or a fast or irregular heartbeat that doesn't settle. When in doubt about a sudden change, it's always safer to be checked promptly."
    },
    "disclaimer": "This summary is generated by a computer model to help you understand your health information. It is not a diagnosis and not a substitute for advice from a qualified clinician. Always talk to your healthcare provider about your results and any decisions."
  },
